San Francisco Wild Parrot Data

Hello! This Jupyter Notebook is used to access and view data about the San Francisco Wild Parrots! The San Francisco Wild Parrots are known by their distincitve green bodies, red colored heads, and loud calls. First making appearances in the 1990s, these Cherry-headed conures (Psittacara erythrogenys) are not native to San Francisco and are believed to have originated from Ecuador and Peru. In this Notebook, we'll take a closer look at the sightings of these special parrots in San Francisco. We will access this data through the BirdData module that's been provided.

Getting Started

First, let's import the Data class from the BirdData module and assign it to the data variable. The Data class opens and cleans the data related to parrot sightings around San Francisco.

In[]:
from BirdData import Data
data = Data()

Next, we'll view all of the recorded sightings in a DataFrame. To do this, we'll access the sightings attribute of our Data class.

In[]:
data.sightings

Searching for the Parrots

The Data class of the BirdData module has several methods to find where the parrots are sighted the most.

Most Frequent Locations

The most_freq_loc() method returns a list of tuples containing the neighborhood and coordinates that the parrots are sighted the most throughout San Francisco. It also displays a map showing those coordinates. Let's iterate through that list and print the map.

In[]:
for location in data.most_freq_loc():
    print(f'Coordinates: (Latitude: {location[1]}, Longitude: {location[2]})')
    print(f'Neighborhood: {location[0]}')
    print()

So, according to this list, which location had the most sightings of the parrots? If you want know where a specific location is, just copy and paste those coordinates in Google Maps and maybe you'll see the parrots there!

Searching By Season

Another method we can use is the by_season() method. The method takes a parameter, which is a string that represents a season. The method returns a tuple containing the locations the parrots are most frequently seen during a given season, the amount of sightings during a a given season, and the percentage of total sightings that take are reported during a given season. For the sake of this dataset, we have divided the seasons as follows: winter will return the locations the parrots frequent the most during the months of December, January, February. spring will return the most frequent locations during March, April and May. summer corresponds to the months of June, July, and August. fall corresponds to the months of September, October, and November. For this example, we'll check the Spring months. Change the season variable to see the corresponding season!

In[]:
season = 'spring'
for location in data.by_season(season)[0]:
    print(f'Coordinates: (Latitude: {location[1]}, Longitude: {location[2]})')
    print(f'Neighborhood: {location[0]}')
    print()
print(f'During the {season} seasons, there were {data.by_season(season)[1]} sightings of the parrots, which is about {data.by_season(season)[2]:.2f}% of all sightings.')

Coordinates: (Latitude: 37.80518, Longitude: -122.42855)
Neighborhood: Aquatic Park / Ft. Mason

Coordinates: (Latitude: 37.791473, Longitude: -122.42735)

During the spring seasons, there were 3046 sightings of the parrots, which is about 27.36% of all sightings.

While there are some common locations across all the seasons, there is definitely some variation throughout the year.

Frequent Locations Within Neighborhoods

Now that we have our list of neighborhoods, we can use the most_at_location() method to find the most common location the parrots are found in a given neighborhood. The most_at_location() method takes a neighborhood string as a parameter and returns a tuple containing the neighborhood name and the coordinates of the most common location the parrots are spotted in that neighborhood. For this example, let's check the most common location the birds are spotted at in the Financial District and then format it. First, we'll create a new variable called neighborhood and assign it the string Financial District. (Caution: Neighborhoods are case-sensitive and must be spelled correctly. We advise copying the neighborhood from the list and pasting it to the neighborhood variable.)

In[]:
neighborhood = 'Financial District'

Next, we'll assign most_at_location(neighborhood) to a new variable locs. Then we can format the information.

In[]:
locs = data.most_at_location(neighborhood)
print(f'The parrots are spotted most frequently at the coordinates (Latitude: {locs[1]}, Longitude: {locs[2]}) in the {neighborhood} area.')

The parrots are spotted most frequently at the coordinates (Latitude: 37.79593, Longitude: -122.39647) in the Financial District area.

Number of Sightings in a Neighborhood

Using the no_in_neighborhood() method, we can find the number of times that the parrots have been spotted in the neighborhood given as the parameter. In this example, we'll continue examining the Financial District and then formatting the information.

In[]:
print(f'Number of sightings in the {neighborhood} area: {data.no_in_neighborhood(neighborhood)}')

Number of sightings in the Financial District area: 714

Percent of Total Sightings

Another method relating to neighborhood is the percent_of_sightings() method which returns the percentage of sightings that have been at the neighborhood given as a parameter. The method returns a float. Let's try it out with the Financial District.

In[]:
print(f'About {data.percent_of_sightings(neighborhood):.2f}% of all parrot sightings in San Francisco have been in the {neighborhood} area.')

About 6.41% of all parrot sightings in San Francisco have been in the Financial District area.

Distribution of Sightings

One last method in the Data class in the BirdData module is the neighborhood_distribution() method. This method prints out a map that allows us to visualize the distribution the parrot sightings around San Francisco.

In[]:
data.neighborhood_distribution()

As you can see, there are some neighborhoods that the parrots really favor!
